that took place in 1997 in Roswell, New Mexico, and it was a scene because we had, like,

01:50:59.620 --> 01:51:04.320
members of Congress, there was Congressman Schiff, I think it was, who was saying, like,

01:51:04.420 --> 01:51:09.380
I don't know what's going on here, but I've been getting, you know, I've been getting,

01:51:09.500 --> 01:51:13.300
I've been getting, like, stiff-armed by the Air Force, you know, and I'm making inquiries

01:51:13.300 --> 01:51:18.220
and why would you fly, you know, a weather balloon under armed guard, like, you know.

01:51:18.220 --> 01:51:21.120
And he noted that all of the Roswell stuff was deleted.

01:51:21.320 --> 01:51:21.740
Oh, yeah, yeah.

01:51:21.920 --> 01:51:23.080
All of the archival material in the government.

01:51:23.220 --> 01:51:25.780
And they sent him to an agency knowing that agency didn't have anything.

01:51:25.900 --> 01:51:29.000
And this was all happening, more people were coming forward, and then, boom,

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:36.140
this guy, you know, Philip Corso, who apparently, according to him, he told me this directly

01:51:36.140 --> 01:51:42.800
from his mouth to my ears, he said that they rushed the book to print with William Burns

01:51:42.800 --> 01:51:46.180
because they wanted to make the, they wanted to ride the coattails of the 50th anniversary

01:51:46.180 --> 01:51:49.660
of Roswell and all the attention it was getting, and that there were a lot of discrepancies

01:51:49.660 --> 01:51:54.160
in the book that he was upset about, that, you know, this is what he told me.

01:51:54.160 --> 01:52:00.760
And, and I, uh, when he came to Roswell, there was a flurry of activity in one of the hangars

01:52:00.760 --> 01:52:04.960
and he was surrounded by all these news reporters.

01:52:05.140 --> 01:52:07.280
Oh my Lord, you should have seen it was a feeding frenzy.

01:52:07.280 --> 01:52:11.120
Like, and I'm looking at him and I'm like, I got to get a, I got to get an on-camera

01:52:11.120 --> 01:52:15.160
statement, but I was a little kid with a camera and I was like, you know what, I'm just going

01:52:15.160 --> 01:52:16.140
to elbow my way in there.

01:52:16.160 --> 01:52:16.540
I don't care.

01:52:16.580 --> 01:52:20.360
And I, I fought my way in there and I got my camera and I asked them a couple of questions

01:52:20.360 --> 01:52:20.880
in the movie.

01:52:20.940 --> 01:52:21.460
I'll give it to you.

01:52:21.480 --> 01:52:22.020
You can show it.

01:52:22.640 --> 01:52:26.320
And, um, and then the next day I found out where he was staying, what hotel he was in.

01:52:27.500 --> 01:52:28.960
And I, I just like, you know what?

01:52:29.060 --> 01:52:32.200
I went to the reception and I said, oh, I've got a meeting with Philip Corso.

01:52:32.380 --> 01:52:33.820
Can you, I just forgot what room he's in.

01:52:33.860 --> 01:52:34.240
Would you mind?

01:52:34.340 --> 01:52:40.220
You know, and I went to the room and, um, oh, we were expecting you.

01:52:40.260 --> 01:52:42.800
Like, you know, and, uh, oh, really?

01:52:42.960 --> 01:52:47.480
Like I was like, so we sit down and we do an hour and a half long interview, whatever it

01:52:47.480 --> 01:52:50.880
was, I don't know, hour, hour and a half, got a lot of stuff out of him.

01:52:51.000 --> 01:52:53.180
Again, I'll, I'm happy to provide whatever you want.

01:52:53.820 --> 01:53:01.180
And, um, and then Michael Hesseman arrives, German guy, and he was late and he was all

01:53:01.180 --> 01:53:02.540
sweaty and flustered.

01:53:02.900 --> 01:53:08.420
And apparently he had scheduled the interview that I got with Corso, but he showed up late.

01:53:08.420 --> 01:53:10.460
I showed up, I was in the right place at the right time.

01:53:10.580 --> 01:53:14.360
So I got this sit down interview with Corso when Michael Hesseman should have had it.

01:53:14.400 --> 01:53:17.420
And as it turns out, he was all flustered and he was late and he had no sound.

01:53:17.480 --> 01:53:22.700
So I gave him my sound gear because then I got about, I would say it's about an hour

01:53:22.700 --> 01:53:23.080
and a half.

01:53:23.160 --> 01:53:25.520
And he talked about why he's coming forward because it was grandkids.

01:53:25.620 --> 01:53:27.700
And he's like, I'm old, I'm going to die soon.

01:53:27.780 --> 01:53:32.140
But, you know, I want the world to know if this thing happened, I was a witness, I saw.

01:53:32.540 --> 01:53:36.300
And I remember thinking, cause there was a lot of controversy after he died and he was

01:53:36.300 --> 01:53:40.420
no longer in a position to kind of correct the record, I guess.

01:53:41.460 --> 01:53:42.480
But I believed him.

01:53:42.780 --> 01:53:43.540
I believed him.

01:53:43.600 --> 01:53:45.780
I looked him in the eyes and I really did believe him.

01:53:45.780 --> 01:53:48.260
And I think I still believe him to this day.

01:53:48.460 --> 01:53:52.240
And I think he got a really bad rap and maybe it was too much too soon.

01:53:52.320 --> 01:53:52.860
I don't know.

01:53:53.000 --> 01:53:55.160
But he told me I'm coming forward for my grandchildren.

01:53:55.640 --> 01:53:57.020
And he goes, I saw the bodies.

01:53:57.140 --> 01:54:01.100
Like he looked like a little kid, big head, big eye, you know, all the typical spindly

01:54:01.100 --> 01:54:02.040
arms, spindly legs.

01:54:02.120 --> 01:54:02.740
How many fingers?

01:54:03.180 --> 01:54:04.600
Didn't, I don't remember that part.

01:54:04.600 --> 01:54:06.160
Because, you know, it's interesting.

01:54:06.560 --> 01:54:09.720
You say in, in Virginia, there were three, three fingers.

01:54:09.720 --> 01:54:09.920
Three digits.

01:54:10.100 --> 01:54:10.280
Yeah.

01:54:10.420 --> 01:54:15.200
And, and it was, uh, you know, on the, the paper it's drawn, you know, the three fingers

01:54:15.200 --> 01:54:16.500
or whatever you recreate it.

01:54:16.780 --> 01:54:22.920
And, you know, I've seen beings in Peru that are skeletons with three fingers and the three

01:54:22.920 --> 01:54:24.380
toes and three, three fingers.

01:54:24.640 --> 01:54:28.620
And they carbon date to between 800 and 1700 years ago.

01:54:28.620 --> 01:54:32.400
And one of them has a tridactyl fetus inside of it.

01:54:32.540 --> 01:54:33.820
So there's inheritance between.

01:54:33.940 --> 01:54:34.580
What does tridactyl mean?

01:54:34.860 --> 01:54:36.020
Tridactyl means three fingers.

01:54:36.640 --> 01:54:41.980
So, so one of them has a, a, a fetus with three fingers and three toes in it.

01:54:44.520 --> 01:54:44.960
Wow.

01:54:46.860 --> 01:54:51.120
They all have DNA associated with them and further testing is being done right now.

01:54:51.300 --> 01:54:54.720
So I'm like, okay, both of these things are happening in South America.

01:54:55.340 --> 01:54:58.140
Is that just a skeleton of what?

01:54:58.140 --> 01:55:01.960
And they have, they have elongated heads, but they didn't undergo any head binding.

01:55:02.120 --> 01:55:04.620
They don't have any of the stress fractures involved in head binding.

01:55:05.020 --> 01:55:05.460
Wow.

01:55:05.860 --> 01:55:07.020
Super weird.

01:55:07.280 --> 01:55:10.940
Barginia, Brazil, those things had three fingers and three toes.

01:55:11.500 --> 01:55:12.620
So the question is like.

01:55:12.620 --> 01:55:14.240
And they saw footprints too in that case.

01:55:14.340 --> 01:55:19.940
And, and, and didn't Dave Grush say that some of the craft recovered were archaeological digs

01:55:19.940 --> 01:55:20.840
or something like this?

01:55:20.960 --> 01:55:22.880
He said, uh, Bob Lazar said that.

01:55:22.880 --> 01:55:23.300
Bob Lazar said that.

01:55:23.300 --> 01:55:29.240
But David Grush said that the, that the, the, the skeletons that I saw in Peru looked

01:55:29.240 --> 01:55:32.180
like things that he'd seen in classified settings.

01:55:32.900 --> 01:55:33.300
Wow.

01:55:33.460 --> 01:55:37.340
So that could be the same thing that happened in Virginia, that, that being, and we could

01:55:37.340 --> 01:55:39.920
have literal mummies of those beings.

01:55:40.580 --> 01:55:41.460
For all we know.

01:55:41.620 --> 01:55:42.060
Bigelow.

01:55:42.060 --> 01:55:43.140
I remember I met with Bigelow.

01:55:43.220 --> 01:55:48.420
I got contacted by him in 2009 and I don't think I was ready for what he told me at the

01:55:48.420 --> 01:55:48.740
time.

01:55:48.800 --> 01:55:51.080
And I'm quite honestly, I don't know if I'm still not ready.

01:55:51.340 --> 01:55:51.880
What did he say?

01:55:52.340 --> 01:55:56.040
Well, it was funny actually, because he talked about the complexities of disclosure.

01:55:56.160 --> 01:55:58.060
He reached out to me through his secretary.

01:55:58.060 --> 01:56:03.560
I still have the email and they said, uh, uh, Mr. Bigelow wants to congratulate you on a

01:56:03.560 --> 01:56:05.640
job well done for, I know what I saw.

01:56:06.360 --> 01:56:07.600
And, uh, that's cool.

01:56:07.700 --> 01:56:11.180
I looked up Bigelow and I kind of knew who, you know, I was like, oh, wow.

01:56:11.860 --> 01:56:13.660
Would Mr. Bigelow like to get together?

01:56:13.860 --> 01:56:15.000
You know, yes, he would actually.

01:56:15.140 --> 01:56:20.980
And so we arranged a time and I would go to his house and this is like 2009 probably.

01:56:20.980 --> 01:56:28.540
And, uh, we had lunch together at his house in Las Vegas and he, he starts telling me about

01:56:28.540 --> 01:56:29.980
the complexities of disclosure.

01:56:30.100 --> 01:56:31.140
Do you understand kid?

01:56:31.220 --> 01:56:37.000
Like, you know, the implications and they're so vast impacts on organized religion and this

01:56:37.000 --> 01:56:37.400
and that.

01:56:37.560 --> 01:56:42.380
And I, I honestly, I hadn't really thought of the complexities of disclosure and I was

01:56:42.380 --> 01:56:43.000
like, yeah, cool.

01:56:43.080 --> 01:56:44.040
You know, and he's talking about that.

01:56:44.080 --> 01:56:46.420
And then he goes, he goes, uh, yeah.

01:56:46.420 --> 01:56:47.580
And they're walking among us.

01:56:47.580 --> 01:56:51.140
And I said, what?

01:56:51.520 --> 01:56:54.200
And he goes, what do you mean?

01:56:54.860 --> 01:56:57.240
You know, he goes, I mean, exactly that.

01:56:57.300 --> 01:56:58.760
They're, they're walking among us.

01:56:59.280 --> 01:57:03.420
Now, now I think I took that and I put it in the back of my head.

01:57:03.420 --> 01:57:04.280
Cause I was like, you know what?

01:57:04.320 --> 01:57:05.200
That's just crazy.

01:57:05.240 --> 01:57:06.500
Like, you gotta be kidding me.

01:57:06.540 --> 01:57:08.560
You know, at the time, I don't know.

01:57:08.740 --> 01:57:09.720
I took it with a grain of salt.

01:57:12.120 --> 01:57:13.940
Uh, maybe they are.

01:57:14.000 --> 01:57:14.440
I don't know.

01:57:14.440 --> 01:57:19.040
I mean, it would be pretty funny if they were, because, you know, here we are looking

01:57:19.040 --> 01:57:25.900
out across the cosmos for any sign of intelligent life, you know, with all the various NASA

01:57:25.900 --> 01:57:31.600
programs, you know, looking, uh, for water or whatever oxygen or atmosphere, you know,

01:57:31.640 --> 01:57:32.420
all these various planets.

01:57:32.420 --> 01:57:37.020
And then it would be funny if they're like right here, you know, and maybe they are,

01:57:37.160 --> 01:57:38.680
you know, maybe they are.

01:57:38.680 --> 01:57:43.340
Yeah, well, they, the, Hal Puthoff always talks about the UFOs engaging in what he calls

01:57:43.340 --> 01:57:49.040
signature management, where they control what they sort of look like or appear to be an

01:57:49.040 --> 01:57:50.580
optical and radar and that sort of thing.

01:57:50.680 --> 01:57:54.240
And so maybe that's happening with the beings themselves.

01:57:54.460 --> 01:57:56.020
And so who knows?

01:57:56.020 --> 01:58:02.660
One thing that I've learned over the decades is suspend judgment, man.

01:58:02.700 --> 01:58:04.240
At this point, anything's possible.

01:58:05.180 --> 01:58:06.740
I don't know what's going on.

01:58:06.940 --> 01:58:08.920
I would love to know what's going on.

01:58:09.900 --> 01:58:10.740
I don't either.

01:58:10.940 --> 01:58:16.400
And I, and I want you guys to understand, like, I don't put something out into the public

01:58:16.400 --> 01:58:19.880
if I don't believe it's highly likely that it happened.

01:58:19.980 --> 01:58:22.320
I'm not out there just trying to, I really don't.

01:58:22.420 --> 01:58:23.280
I care about integrity.

01:58:23.440 --> 01:58:24.980
I care about perception.

01:58:24.980 --> 01:58:26.360
You're the opposite of a grifter.

01:58:26.400 --> 01:58:32.400
A grifter doesn't start valeting cars and then makes the thing on the side because he's

01:58:32.400 --> 01:58:33.620
so passionate about it.

01:58:33.740 --> 01:58:35.080
What are you talking about?

01:58:35.280 --> 01:58:38.640
When there is no market for the thing in the early 2000s.

01:58:38.680 --> 01:58:42.560
Once I pay back my investors, I always put my films on free platforms.

01:58:42.840 --> 01:58:43.220
Like, free!

01:58:43.220 --> 01:58:47.060
No, you just, you just told me before you started rolling, your dream is to buy the phenomenon

01:58:47.060 --> 01:58:47.700
back.

01:58:47.700 --> 01:58:47.980
Yeah, I know.

01:58:48.360 --> 01:58:49.440
So how are you a grifter?

01:58:49.540 --> 01:58:53.000
You want to buy your own footage back because that feels more authentic.

01:58:53.000 --> 01:58:53.580
It's crazy.

01:58:53.660 --> 01:58:54.040
Yeah, anyway.

01:58:54.040 --> 01:58:56.420
So, yeah, that's just ridiculous.

01:58:57.420 --> 01:59:02.940
No, but it is, these things, same with this thing in Peru, with these mummies, like, sometimes

01:59:02.940 --> 01:59:07.420
when the thing is staring you in the face, you think it's too good to be true, but maybe

01:59:07.420 --> 01:59:12.020
it's just, you know, Jim Semivan, who's very high up at the CIA, he said, he says, like,

01:59:12.140 --> 01:59:14.640
most of this stuff is a personal experience.

01:59:14.640 --> 01:59:17.600
He says, most of this stuff is just hidden in plain sight.

01:59:17.800 --> 01:59:20.520
And that's the conclusion that I've come to.

01:59:21.440 --> 01:59:22.600
Again, despite my-

01:59:22.600 --> 01:59:23.420
It's so funny, wouldn't it?

01:59:23.920 --> 01:59:24.220
Yeah.

01:59:24.540 --> 01:59:24.780
Right?

01:59:24.980 --> 01:59:25.220
What?

01:59:25.460 --> 01:59:26.840
It's just, it's just there.

01:59:26.840 --> 01:59:32.600
I was at the airport a couple years ago, and I was flying to Arizona for a conference or

01:59:32.600 --> 01:59:37.460
something, and I get up to the gate, and I was like, shit, I left my sunglasses in the

01:59:37.460 --> 01:59:37.880
car.

01:59:38.040 --> 01:59:39.540
It's like, I can't leave without my sunglasses.

01:59:39.720 --> 01:59:41.640
It's like, ah, I had to go back to the security.

01:59:41.800 --> 01:59:42.780
I got all the way out of the car.

01:59:42.940 --> 01:59:44.220
Ah, my sunglasses aren't there.

01:59:44.300 --> 01:59:46.160
I was like, crap, guess where they were?

01:59:46.680 --> 01:59:46.900
Where?

01:59:47.060 --> 01:59:47.800
On my face.

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:48.260
Yeah.

01:59:48.260 --> 01:59:50.940
They were right there.

01:59:51.000 --> 01:59:52.960
Yeah, sometimes it's just staring at you.

01:59:52.960 --> 01:59:53.660
Right there.

01:59:53.880 --> 01:59:59.400
But what is, did you probe Bigelow more, and you say, what did you mean exactly by-

01:59:59.400 --> 02:00:00.360
I talked about the implications.

02:00:00.360 --> 02:00:00.720
They're walking among us.

02:00:00.800 --> 02:00:05.040
Well, I did talk about the implications of disclosure, the complications of disclosure

02:00:05.040 --> 02:00:09.000
a little bit, but in terms of them walking among us, I wasn't ready for it.

02:00:09.680 --> 02:00:10.560
I honestly wasn't.

02:00:10.660 --> 02:00:12.400
I was like, you know, who's this guy?

02:00:12.900 --> 02:00:13.640
I don't know, man.

02:00:13.640 --> 02:00:19.040
I couldn't dismiss it entirely just because of his position.

02:00:19.200 --> 02:00:24.880
He's probably invested more money in research with NIDS and OSAP and ATIP and all the various

02:00:24.880 --> 02:00:26.300
different people that he's worked with.

02:00:27.060 --> 02:00:31.560
So I couldn't, like, I didn't categorically dismiss it, but I kind of put it, I compartmentalized

02:00:31.560 --> 02:00:32.500
it and put it at the back of my head.

02:00:33.580 --> 02:00:40.060
But as time went by and I learned more about the phenomenon, I started thinking, shit, man,

02:00:40.100 --> 02:00:40.840
maybe he's right.

02:00:41.360 --> 02:00:43.600
Maybe they are right here, you know?

02:00:43.640 --> 02:00:44.520
Walking among us.

02:00:44.640 --> 02:00:46.140
Wouldn't that be funny?

02:00:46.840 --> 02:00:47.060
You know?

02:00:47.560 --> 02:00:50.400
It's like, you know, it's right under our noses.

02:00:50.560 --> 02:00:52.180
There it is, in plain sight.

02:00:52.540 --> 02:00:58.360
And that seems to make more sense to me because a lot of people go, you know, and I get people

02:00:58.360 --> 02:01:01.480
go, oh, well, you're just, you know, you're concluding, you know, it's extraterrestrial.

02:01:01.660 --> 02:01:04.300
I was like, no, actually, I didn't say that and I've never said that.

02:01:04.460 --> 02:01:05.860
I really don't know what they are.

02:01:05.980 --> 02:01:12.620
Well, with a guy who's transporting this being in this, you know, military cargo driver or whatever,

02:01:12.620 --> 02:01:13.580
he goes...

02:01:13.580 --> 02:01:14.280
I'll show you the email.

02:01:14.820 --> 02:01:15.920
I want to see that email.

02:01:16.160 --> 02:01:16.720
Yeah, sorry, go ahead.

02:01:16.820 --> 02:01:21.500
But he says, he says it was, you know, it was told to him like there was somebody was

02:01:21.500 --> 02:01:22.040
questioning him.

02:01:22.120 --> 02:01:22.820
What'd you see?

02:01:23.060 --> 02:01:23.220
Right.

02:01:23.220 --> 02:01:25.020
And he says, I don't know what I saw.

02:01:25.120 --> 02:01:27.040
You know, it was like a burnt human being or something.

02:01:27.040 --> 02:01:28.360
Because he was trying to be coy.

02:01:28.500 --> 02:01:30.160
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

02:01:30.160 --> 02:01:31.360
It was super natural.

02:01:31.360 --> 02:01:37.720
They focused on me with this other military guy.

02:01:38.280 --> 02:01:42.400
He looked me right in the eyes and asked what I had seen.

02:01:44.100 --> 02:01:47.020
I said, I think it was a burnt man or something.

02:01:47.020 --> 02:02:00.280
He said, I don't know if he thought I was trying to deceive him, you know, like he knows,

02:02:00.520 --> 02:02:02.820
but he just doesn't want to talk about it.

02:02:04.480 --> 02:02:09.160
It was then that he stated that what I had witnessed was a particular thing.

02:02:10.240 --> 02:02:11.400
Super natural.

02:02:11.400 --> 02:02:16.680
Yeah, super natural.

02:02:16.920 --> 02:02:18.240
Super natural, yeah.

02:02:18.500 --> 02:02:21.920
I was very funny in the edit room because I edit my own movies.

02:02:22.740 --> 02:02:25.000
And that line just really stuck with me.

02:02:25.120 --> 02:02:29.420
And I really wanted it to hit with the audience.

02:02:29.880 --> 02:02:34.520
And so I did all the subtitles in the film.

02:02:34.580 --> 02:02:36.460
And I did it at my pacing because I'm a slow reader.

02:02:36.700 --> 02:02:40.320
And it always frustrates me when I'm watching a film with subtitles when they come on too fast.

02:02:40.320 --> 02:02:41.660
I'm like, nah, you're going too fast.

02:02:41.900 --> 02:02:42.320
Slow down.

02:02:42.680 --> 02:02:47.020
So I tried to like do one line whenever I could, two lines at most, primarily one line.

02:02:47.960 --> 02:02:51.320
And when it came to super, because he goes, this is Military X,

02:02:51.540 --> 02:02:55.180
talking about with the general meeting that he had with the general after he'd driven this creature

02:02:55.180 --> 02:02:58.900
from various places, Humanitas, ultimately Campinas.

02:02:59.560 --> 02:03:03.320
And he's like, he goes, no, no, that's not what you saw.

02:03:03.420 --> 02:03:05.520
What you saw was super natural.

02:03:05.520 --> 02:03:10.640
And so I put super, and then a beat later, natural, as he said it on the text.

02:03:12.000 --> 02:03:17.260
And then the other guy that I worked with, Boris, he changed it to have them both come on at the same time.

02:03:17.280 --> 02:03:19.280
And I went, no, no, no, no, no, Boris, that was intentional.

02:03:19.580 --> 02:03:22.360
I want that word because it's memorable, right?

